were committed to their own fight for equality during this period, crossed racial, socioeconomic, geographic, and ideological divides to align themselves with a union of predominantly Mexican American farm workers in rural California. Lauren Araiza considers the history, ideology, and political engagement of these five civil rights organizations, representing a broad spectrum of African American activism, and compares their attitudes and approaches to multiracial coalitions. Through their various relationships with the UFW, Araiza examines the dynamics of race, class, labor, and politics in twentieth-century freedom movements. The lessons in this eloquent and provocative study apply to a broader understanding of political and ethnic coalition building in the contemporary United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxRelations with Mexican AmericansxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican American agricultural laborersxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAfrican Studies.  aAfrican-American Studies.  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220883240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812208832423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812208832.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Com